did.unittitle: Office of Human Resources and Affirmative Action (University of Michigan) Promotion Casebooks 1961-ongoing
did.abstract: Hard copy and digital promotion casebooks for University of Michigan faculty and research staff at the Ann Arbor, Dearborn, and Flint campuses.

repository.corpname: Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan

acqinfo.p: Records were transferred from Human Resources and Affirmative Action and its predecessor, the Personnel Office (Donor No. 7384) in various accessions. Additions are regularly received.

accruals.p: Periodic additions to the records are expected.

accessrestrict.p: The Promotion Casebooks records consist of personnel records of University of Michigan faculty members and are subject to personnel records restrictions. The Promotion Casebooks are closed for 30 years from date of creation.

The Promotion Casebooks record group includes restricted material in the following categories:
Personnel Related Records -- Boxes 3-108 and in digital format.

userestrict.p: Copyright is held by the Regents of the University of Michigan.

prefercite.p: [item], folder, box, Office of Human Resources and Affirmative Action (University of Michigan) Promotion Casebooks, Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan

processinfo.p: The hard copy promotion records were typically received in 3-ring binders. For storage and preservation purposes, for some years, the records were removed from the notebooks. References to “books” are retained in the contents list, but the contents now exist in archival folders.

bioghist.p: In February 1994, the Personnel Office and the Affirmative Action Office were combined into a new entity, Human Resources and Affirmative Action (HRAA). The University of Michigan Personnel Office, the oldest of the two units merged into HRAA, was established in 1945. HRAA formally reports to the Provost and Executive Vice President for Academic Affairs. Among HRAA's many responsibilities are the development and implementation of the university's personnel policies, administration of the faculty promotion and tenure granting process, and negotiation and administration of contracts with unionized university employees.

Recommendations for faculty promotions and granting of tenure are initiated by the department, division, college or school. These recommendations are transmitted through Academic Human Resources and Affirmative Action to the President and to the Provost and Executive Vice President for Academic Affairs, and then to the Board of Regents for final action.

For further history of the Personnel Office and Affirmative Action Office, including information on tenure and promotion policies and procedures, researchers are advised to consult the following finding aids: University of Michigan. Personnel Office, University of Michigan. Affirmative Action Office, and University of Michigan Office of Human Resources and Affirmative Action.

scopecontent.p: This record group, Promotion Casebooks, consists of files on faculty members recommended by deans of colleges, schools, or divisions to the Board of Regents for promotion and/or tenure. Each individual's file typically includes the notification of the Regents decision in the case, the promotion recommendation from the dean, a curriculum vitae, and letters of recommendation. The records are arranged chronologically by academic year and thereunder by academic unit. Larger schools and colleges, namely College of Engineering; College of Literature, Science and the Arts; and the Medical School, are subdivided by department or division. Files for UM-Dearborn and UM-Flint campuses are usually located at the end of each year. Particularly for the later years, as the files become more voluminous, additional features may be present such as examples of research or teaching evaluations. In some cases there is some blurring of the academic year or the promotion file was held back. For that reasons those seeking a particular file may be compelled to look in one or more years to locate the file. The casebooks are restricted for thirty years from date of creation.
